1. What is a default method in an interface?

Answer:

A default method is a method in an interface with a body.
Introduced in Java 8.
Declared using the default keyword.
Implementing classes can use it directly or override it.

Example:

interface Demo {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Default Method");
    }
}

class Test implements Demo {}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test t = new Test();
        t.show();
    }
}



2. Why were default methods introduced in Java 8?
Answer:

To add new methods to existing interfaces without breaking existing implementations.
Maintain backward compatibility.
Support Lambda Expressions and Stream API enhancements.






3. How are default methods different from abstract methods?
-->
| Default Method         | Abstract Method          |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Has implementation     | No implementation        |
| Uses `default` keyword | No keyword               |
| Override is optional   | Override is mandatory    |
| Introduced in Java 8   | Available since Java 1.0 |




4. Can we override a default method in an implementing class?
-->Answer:

      Yes.
          An implementing class can override the default method.
          
          Example:
          
          interface Demo {
              default void show() {
                  System.out.println("Default");
              }
          }
          
          class Test implements Demo {
              @Override
              public void show() {
                  System.out.println("Overridden");
              }
          }





5. What if two interfaces have the same default method name?
Answer:

The implementing class must override the method to resolve the conflict.
You can call a specific interface's default method using InterfaceName.super.methodName().

Example:

interface A {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("A");
    }
}

interface B {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("B");
    }
}

class Test implements A, B {

    @Override
    public void show() {
        A.super.show();
        B.super.show();
    }
}




6. Can we call a default method from another default method?
-->Answer:

      Yes.
      A default method can call another default method in the same interface.
      
      Example:
      
      interface Demo {
      
          default void show() {
              display();
          }
      
          default void display() {
              System.out.println("Display");
          }
      }




